result.execSummary:
The defendant Andre D. Stackhouse was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Attempt 1st-Degree Intentional Homicide [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class B felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.01(1)(a).
  • Aggravated Battery-Intend GreatBod. Harm [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(5).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superMiscConds.notes: The Defendant is to undergo any counseling the agent finds appropriate and must comply with any recommended treatment/assessment/counseling.   The Defendant is ordered to undergo an anger management assessment and follow any recommendations for counseling.  The Defendant is to maintain absolute sobriety - no alcohol or drugs unless prescribed by a physician.  No use or possession of firearms and weapons.  The Defendant is to obtain and maintain full time employment and/or educational programming as recommended. The Defendant is to have no cash jobs.  The Defendant is to have no contact with S.F.   The Defendant is to provide a biological specimen for DNA analysis.  The Defendant is not to go into any bars, taverns or businesses where the primary purpose is to sell alcohol. DOC to provide access to any anger management and other treatment programs available to defendant while he is incarcerated. The defendant not to be present at any businesses on College Avenue, Appleton, WI.   If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due, and/or other collection means, such as income assignment will be issued.
State has 90 days to request restitution.
